<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">It is worthy of attention that although the South and Southwest Coasts of Lake Huron and Lake Michagan are with very few exceptions entirely limestone I have never seen nor heard of a particle of it, in all the circle of Lake Superior<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Surface of the country for many leagues Round S<sup>t</sup> Mar<span class="DelHand-author">ie</span><span class="AddHand-author">y</span>'s is very <span class="DelHand-author">A</span>irregular consisting to the North of Rocky Mountains Marshes and Lakes, to the South of Hills and Swamps<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The good lands are to <span class="AddHand-author">be</span> found along the Rivers and the Skirts of Some few of the mountains<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  There is a hill to the South West of the Village about three miles which is cultivable all over, the Soil is excellent producing Oak and Maple, and the land continues of the Same quality for eight or ten leagues back until it terminates in an extensive marshy plain at present the residence of a few Reindeer and Beaver but which might easily be converted into fine Arrable land and meadow<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The East, North, and Nor<span class="AddHand-author">th</span>west coast of Lake Huron consists of Basaltes and coarse granite.  The bay of Machedash is its extremity to the eastward.  There is a Small River which takes its rise in Lake Sympcoe that falls into the bay but is not navigable all its length on account of a Fall: however I am told the Portage is only three leagues and could be easily made a wag<span class="AddHand-author">g</span>on Road<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Lake Sympcoe is 15 leagues long, is navigable for Small craft, and communicates with the Settlements to the westard of York from</p>

